<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-351-888  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 351 888.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  April 16 1990 n296 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Flight to the future. (the potential of optical technology)(Perspective) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Huang, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>AT and T Bell Laboratories is working on the commercialdevelopment of the first digital optical processor.andP;  The key tooptical technology, whether applied to information processing orcommunications, is the employment of beams of laser light ratherthan electricity to drive the machine.andP;  The processor that AT andT demonstrated uses laser beams to move the information through aseries of self electro-optic effect devices (SEEDS), which are theequivalent of logic gates.andP;  This technology provides a notableincrease in bandwidth, offering 1,000 to 10,000 times theprocessing power of electronics technology and opening the door todata transmission switches with terabit (1 trillion bits persecond) capacity.andP;  A single photon-guiding lens offers thecapacity of 10,000 optic fibers, the equivalent of all thetelephone wires in the world today.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Bell Laboratories Inc. (research).andO;Topic:     Optical CommunicationsOptical ComputersInformation ProcessingBandwidthTransmission SpeedLaser and Infrared CommunicationResearch and Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>